A.  Component 1: Strengthening the Basic Education Policy Framework (29 person-
months) 

1.  Design of Working Group Profiles and Selection Procedures (1 specialist for 
0.5 person-months) 

1.  The specialist will 

(i)  work with lead specialists nominated by the Ministry of Public Education (MOPE) 
for curriculum, assessment, Information and Communication Technology (ICT), 
and Language of Instruction (LOI) to define the ideal membership profile of each 
working group and subgroup; 
(ii)  develop  terms  of  reference  for  working  group  membership  and  finalize  with 
support from the Project Implementation Unit (PIU) and MOPE the detailed job 
descriptions and terms and conditions of membership; and 
(iii)  develop  candidate  evaluation  scheme  and  design  selection  criteria  and 
procedures. 

2.  Support to National Curriculum Framework Working Group (two specialists 
for a total of 7.5 person-months)  

2.  The specialists will 

(i)  provide  initial  training  to  all  members  of  the  national  curriculum  framework 
working group on the principles and practice of curriculum review and design; 
(ii)  identify  and  prepare  relevant  case  studies  on  curriculum  review  from  other 
countries for discussion; 
(iii)  identify and prepare summaries of other relevant curricula for discussion and the 
identify pros and cons; 
(iv)  establish for working group members the cost implications of curriculum design; 
(v)  assist working group members to clearly identify their priority objectives; 
(vi)  assist  working  group members  develop  a  clear  concept  of  the  purpose  and 
function of a draft national curriculum framework; 
(vii)  assist working group members develop a work program with intermediate targets 
and deadlines to achieve their aims; 
(viii)  assist in the specification and design of required research work and studies; 
(ix)  help identify study tour destinations with the rationale for each destination; 
(x)  provide ongoing support during the process of review; and 
(xi)  help draft the curriculum review report and recommendations. 

  3.  Syllabus Development Support (seven specialists comprising local language 
and  literature,  foreign  language,  mathematics,  science,  social  sciences, 
economics, business studies, ICT and arts for a total of 14 person-months)   

3.  On completion of the review and recommendations subject specialists will 

(i)  work with subject specialist working group members on the required content 
amendments to subject syllabi; 
(ii)  help identify key skills and competencies; 
(iii)  help specify and incorporate relevant learning objectives and outputs into the 
syllabi;

  Appendix 13  51
(iv)  help  develop  appropriate  vertical  sequencing  within  subject  syllabi  and  the 
horizontal integration between subjects; 
(v)  identify appropriate learning and teaching methodologies and learning activities; 
and 
(vi)  help specify performance and achievement criteria for assessment purposes.  

  4.  Support to Assessment Subgroup (one specialist for 4 person-months)  

4.  The specialist will 

(i)  provide  initial  training  to  all  members  of  the  assessment  subgroup  on  the 
purposes, principles, and practice of assessment and examination review; 
(ii)  identify  and  prepare  relevant  case  studies  on  alternative  approaches  to 
assessment from other countries for discussion, paying particular attention to 
assessment and examination reform in other former Soviet Union countries and 
within the Central Asian republics; 
(iii)  identify and prepare summaries of other relevant assessment systems for 
discussion and the identification of pros and cons; 
(iv)  establish for group members the cost implications of alternative approaches to 
assessment and examinations; 
(v)  help group members develop a clear concept of the purpose and function of the 
review; 
(vi)  help group members develop a work program with intermediate targets and 
deadlines to achieve their aims; 
(vii)  help specify and design required research work and studies; 
(viii)  help identify study tour destinations with the rationale for each destination; 
(ix)  provide ongoing support during the process of review; and 
(x)  help draft the assessment review report and recommendations. 

  5.  Support to Language Of Instruction Subgroup (one specialist for 3 person-
months) 

5.  The specialist will 

(i)  provide initial training to all members of the subgroup on the theory and practice 
of alternative approaches to LOI policies; 
(ii)  identify and prepare relevant case studies on different approaches to LOI from 
other countries for discussion, paying particular attention to the identification of 
strengths and weaknesses, and examples in other FSU countries and within the 
CARs; 
(iii)  establish for group members the cost implications of alternative approaches to 
LOI; 
(iv)  help group members develop a clear concept of the purpose and function of the 
review targets and deadlines to achieve their aims; 
(v)  help specify and design required research work and studies; 
(vi)  help identify study tour destinations with the rationale for each destination; 
(vii)  provide ongoing support during the process of review; and 
help draft the LOI review report and recommendations.

  Appendix 13  53
C.  Component 3: Book Sector Development (13 person-months) 

1.  Development of Short Professional Training Courses for Local Book Trade 
Training Institution (10 specialists for a total of 10 person-months)  

9.  Each specialist will work closely with domestic specialist consultants to 
(i)  prepare course objectives and program; 
(ii)  develop course materials and case studies; 
(iii)  prepare detailed background notes and additional information for local lecturers; 
(iv)  prepare reading lists and website references; 
(v)  train local specialists to be able to deliver the courses; 
(vi)  help translate materials into Uzbek/Russian; and 
(vii)  supervise and moderate the first delivery of the training course. 

2.  Support to the Development of a Competitive Educational Book Trade (one 
specialist for 1.5 person-months)  

10.  The specialist will work closely with the PIU and domestic specialist consultants to 

(i)  review and analyze the prevailing competitive situation in educational publishing 
and printing; 
(ii)  ascertain current Government policies for publishing and printing competition; 
(iii)  identify the major constraints for operating a fully competitive educational book 
trade; 
(iv)  make recommendations for the implementation of competitive conditions; 
(v)  assess the requirements and implications of book trade privatization and make 
proposals for easing the process; and 
(vi)  provide follow-up support as required. 

3.  Support  to  the  Creation  of  Incentives  for  Authorship  and  Publishing 
Development (one specialist for 1.5 person-months)  

11.  The specialist will work closely with the PIU and domestic specialist consultants to 

(i)  review current copyright and remuneration legislation; 
(ii)  discuss and identify current problems and conditions that impact adversely on 
authorship and investment in school textbook development; 
(iii)  make  recommendations  for  any  required  amendments  needed  to  encourage 
authorship development; 
(iv)  make  recommendations  for  any  required  amendments  needed  to  support 
increased title investment in textbook and other learning materials origination; 
and 
(i)  provide follow-up support as required. 

D.  Component 4: School Library Development (15 person-months)   

1.  Development of School Library Policies, Standards, etc. (one specialist for 2 
person-months)

54        Appendix 13 

12.  The specialist will 

(i)  work closely with domestic library consultants to develop a draft national school 
library policy for approval by MOPE; 
(ii)  develop national school library standards; 
(iii)  develop specifications and guidelines for school library upgrading, refurbishment 
and furnishing; 
(iv)  develop school library rules and regulations; 
(v)  develop a school library management handbook; 
(vi)  develop a school library training module; 
(vii)  design a school library stock profile for use in bidding for school library materials; 
(viii)  develop the bid documentation required for school library stock bidding; 
(ix)  develop the evaluation methodology, criteria, and scoring system for the 
selection and procurement of school library titles; and 
(x)  develop a monitoring and evaluation scheme and instruments. 

2.  Development of School Equipment and ICT Policies, Standards, etc. and 
Assistance  to  Curriculum  Working  Group  in  Development  of  an  ICT 
Strategy for Uzbekistan (one specialist for 3 person-months) 

13.  The specialist will 

(i)  work closely with domestic library consultants to develop a draft national school 
library  equipment,  computer,  and  ICT  operational  guidelines  for  approval  by 
MOPE, including rules and regulations for equipment usage in schools; 
(ii)  develop national school computer and ICT standards; 
(iii)  develop rules and regulations for ICT usage in schools; 
(iv)  develop  a  school  library  equipment,  computer,  and  internet  management 
handbook for use in schools; 
(v)  develop a school library training module for school librarians on the teacher and 
student use and management of equipment, computers, and Internet; 
(vi)  design a software profile for use in the prioritization and award of software grants 
from the proposed software development fund; 
(vii)  develop the concept, operational regulations, and applications documentation for 
the software development fund; 
(viii)  develop  the  evaluation  methodology,  criteria,  and  scoring  system  for  the 
selection and award of software development grants; 
(ix)  design the base-line study and impact evaluation studies for the evaluation of the 
impact of computers, Internet, and school libraries usage on teacher/student 
behavior and performance; 
(x)  develop an ICT monitoring and evaluation scheme and instruments; and 
(xi)  work closely with nominated members of the National Curriculum Framework 
Working Group to develop an outline affordable strategy for ICT development in 
the basic education system in Uzbekistan. 

3.  Support to School Library Training, Supervision, and Progress Reviews 
(two specialists for 10 person-months)

  Appendix 13  55
14.  The specialist will work closely with domestic library consultants to 

(i)  design and write a school library management handbook for the use of trainers 
and school librarians; 
(ii)  finalize detailed pilot school library selection criteria; 
(iii)  prepare detailed specifications for the upgrading of school libraries; 
(iv)  prepare and implement a training module for librarian trainers; 
(v)  design annual training schedules to prepare and orient raion methodologists and 
school  librarians  to  the  requirements  and  possibilities  of  upgraded  school 
libraries; 
(vi)  design annual schedules for the monitoring and supervision of school library 
development; 
(vii)  train evaluators of school library materials; 
(viii)  agree  on  school  library  evaluation  instruments  and  schedules  and  assist 
domestic consultants in the preparation of model evaluation reports; and 
(ix)  provide ongoing support on every aspect of school library upgrading as required.
